At the end of the trade, the Prague stock exchange turned negative.
After the fall of Tuesday morning, the Prague stock exchange rectified its losses.
Trades with the shares reached almost half of the usual daily trades.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the trade, the Prague stock exchange resumed its fall from the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the plan for the stabilization of the US financial sector, is also noticeable in our country.
Stocks fall in Asia
The Asian stock markets experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, even though the indices managed, during the day, to erase some of the losses.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange’s Hang Seng Index lost four percent during trading, but later it wiped out some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index following the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 percent as markets closed in Shanghai.
Stocks on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five per cent, but in the end the losses were reduced to 4.3 per cent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
"Hesitation about bailout action in the US will affect financial markets around the world," said Joseph Yam, head of Hong Kong's monetary office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it sets its monetary policy itself, that is, independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are the same as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will be affected.
The Bloodbath of U.S. Stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the plan to support the financial system, to which it should have devoted up to $700 billion (nearly 12 billion pounds).
In this way, lawmakers reject the call for support for President George Bush’s project.
According to Bush, the project should solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath and the major stock indices experienced the biggest drop in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index lost nearly seven per cent, having fallen so far for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress Ceded: US Government Can Inject $700 Billion Into Banks
The leaders of the US Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of the financial aid agreement for the US financial system.
It will be put to a vote early next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a turning point in talks about adopting a bailout in the form of $700 billion (about 12 trillion kroner) in financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
Success, however, is not certain.
Indeed, before they can publish the final version of the law and put it to the vote, the Congressmans must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Regulation Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be put to the vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout will be adopted should be a first major psychological factor to revive financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms through which market support can be effective, a "disillusionment" will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made great progress.
We have settled our differing views on what the market stabilization package should look like,” Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be taken as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of lawmakers met with U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson, in order to give the bottom of the government a final shape.
It is expected to buy from financial firms the unsaleable real estate assets that drive financial firms into considerable losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
“We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We still need to pursue this plan to restore markets, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis is having a significant impact on falling equity markets.
According to the Democratic senator, Harry Reid, lawmakers are making sure Congress reaches a final agreement as early as Sunday.
They want to calm investors before the start of trades in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the decision of Congress could influence Monday’s trades.
However, for the moment, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two houses of the US Congress will proceed to the vote, nor if the negotiations are not likely to remain blocked, at the last moment, by this or that problem.
Lawmakers hope it will be adopted in the coming days.
Nevertheless, the law will still undergo many changes.
The total amount earmarked for the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be available as soon as possible.
But, if Congress will feel that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the option to block the granting of the remaining amount, following two steps: first $100 billion more, then, finally, $350 billion.
Mr. Bush welcomed the progress in the negotiations
Although the president can veto this decision, Congress has the opportunity to put him in the minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain finances for the redemption of bad real estate securities, whose value declined, because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
“All the work is done.
The House of Representatives is expected to be able to pass the law on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday,” said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
Spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chair Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, says lawmakers have agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of contributors from losses, the relief agreement, the unfolding of the plan on the axis of time.
The new law also provides for limiting the said golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establishes a committee, which will oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on the issue and have made significant progress toward a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance for property owners, who have problems to pay.
The government should negotiate new installments in the case of mortgages that it will buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation is going to be very difficult.
“And this is due to the fact that we don’t know what the mechanism and the price of buying back problem assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government,” Marek said this week at the iHNed.cz server.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or at the beginning of next week, is, according to Marek, not that important.
“It is much more important that the congressmen agree, as early as this week, that they support this plan and that they will dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at this time,” Marek stressed.
A fight pushed to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you, how to choose
While virtually every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
However, there are enough reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house an expensive high-end gramophone to put the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl record, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason, for this to happen.
However, if there are vinyl records in your shelves, packed with art rock, jazz or blues, you at least probably dream of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music while on the move, i.e. compressed music, to put it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
There are also categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, the same way a Pink Floyd fan would struggle to support headphones bought for twenty crowns at the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are functions unknown, of course, to most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, telephone calls and sending SMS, it is able to read music and movies, record them, it has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if we take into account smartphones and communicators, you will have in your pocket a small computer.
Since no fridge knows how to grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are practically witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal nature of the mobile is not without its drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the shorter the interval between reloads.
And playing music is one of the most important energy gutters.
Rare are mobiles that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this respect, music players (especially the most rudimentary) are significantly more efficient.
In the case of cheap mobiles, expect them to only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get yourself, to be sure, a second recharge for work - this being valid even for more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, as a result of a reload, of a continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
You can, of course, record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobiles.
As for the players, you do not need, except for the iPod, any software.
Simply fill, through the USB connector, the device with music from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will create a media library themselves, classified according to the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or according to the judgment of the user.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (irriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
When choosing a concrete device, focus on the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if during the day you will listen to it only for a limited time, for example when taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading MP3.
Virtually all mobiles are capable of this today.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to play.
All are able to play MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have this format.
It is one of the most popular formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices manage to play WMA format music as well.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods), meanwhile, is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Just visit, from the mobile phone, the web pages of the operator (or those of another provider) and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to purchase a music mobile.
The offer of the operators is unfortunately miserable and it is limited, in most cases, to radio tubes quickly made.
The prices are also not the lowest.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether by GSM, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobile phone with them.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to take the mobile out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in speakers, which almost all mobiles have, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of mobile music is its price.
The cheaper ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, one can have an already very suitable walkman.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best equipped, also equipped with an input for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Really anyone manages to ensure the order of the most rudimentary readers - who do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the control to that of a cassette set, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a mobile internet plugged in by chance, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an exchangeable memory card slot (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models in principle only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones do it even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, choose specialized mobile-walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how the ease of control comes close to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles in the walkman series have the same user menu as separately sold MP3 players, is the one that has gone the furthest in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a longer battery life (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned, on Mobil.cz, the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The Czech Telecommunications Office, which has reported that the price of an SMS is higher at home than in the rest of the Union, has confirmed this.
Thus, following the European Commission's latest steps in the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvouk, the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (T.O.), who has stated on several occasions that in the Czech Republic there is no longer room for another operator, made chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with his own network is apparently not very lucky anymore (by the way, now, he would hardly find frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable fall in prices, to which conventional operators must subsequently react.
However, even before the arrival of troublemakers such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those we hear today were heard in Great Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator has managed to gain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let’s add that behind the Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which owns among others the U:fon in Czechia.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be efficient, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
This is how virtual operators around the world present themselves as low-cost operators – they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in Great Britain at least half as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity stunt.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is hard to say, if such a concept would be likely to work in our home as well.
Vodafone’s spokesman Miroslav Cepicko said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very conducive.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area,” said Jana Studnikov, spokesman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were in any case not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that a potential competitor can not appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of corporate customers, does not hide, for quite a long time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already negotiated this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we managed to move forward in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Perhaps the future is promising.
From unofficial information, it looks like we might be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
“At the moment, we do not believe there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific.
For the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this field has contacted us,” mentioned Vlastimil Sr. of Telefonika O2’s press department, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrovo said in a rare deal with the O2 statement: “We have not recorded a viable and bilaterally advantageous project at this time, which could serve as a basis.”
“It is virtually impossible for a virtual operator to appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited period of time, we should have a concrete agreement now.”
Vodafone instead focuses its attention on fulfilling requests to get its own 3G license.
Miroslav says of this: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the field of shared fees and infrastructure.
This is what we believe means the most value from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in tune with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore to a decrease in their profit.
So what is the point of facilitating the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to get along like thieves in fairs. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the T, when the U:fon was created, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the T’s web pages.
However, today, the U:fon lends itself as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrovo commented: "Competition in the mobile market has been further amplified recently by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high demands.
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, it is not only the attitude of the T, which, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power in the Czech Republic to intervene in economic competition.
This is the exclusive responsibility of the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (OHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at this time, because the offer of potential interested parties has not previously shown sufficient interest for conventional operators," said Kristion Chalupa of the OHS Department of External Relations in response to our question.
A statement made in this way would not surprise the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and among other things also take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Even more so when Kristin Chalupa adds: "Foreign countries, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decline in the prices of mobile telephone services."
However, lobbying for honest market operation and lower prices is apparently not in the interests of the OHS.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, naturally arises.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to chance and the hard fight of the competition.
"The Office has not identified any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and therefore none has an increased corresponding responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even from the telecoms regulator,” Chaloupa said in a statement.
One of the many points of contention is the interpretation of the dominant position in the market.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the T, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without accepting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the OHS that three mobile operators are visibly proceeding in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Putting responsibility back on the T is a fairly common trick in communications, by means of which the OHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted Telecommunications Act has not been successfully updated to include a broadening of the Telecommunications Competition Authority's powers in the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts have promised to improve the situation.
This is well known to the representatives of the OHS, but apparently their interests lie elsewhere.
When no one is watching, it can work.
That said, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but these are only partly public.
In most cases, it is about companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Specific mobile telephone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company does in front of the operator figure of a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
“If what you’re talking about happens, it could be a breach of the contractual terms that we’d look at and that could lead to a halt to the collaboration with the company in question,” Kemrov said.
Nevertheless, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity has not reached the heads of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
However, an operator does not rule against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them significant benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Zepicko points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators.
This is precisely what should seem strange to the T.
In addition, there is another question for the OHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the OHS has relatively broad powers to be able to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a considerable drop in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators tried, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were virtually the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It was precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in developed countries intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators but those of their customers.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they ended up getting the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators treat this issue like a hot potato that gets rid of by passing it on to a nearby target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that the confusion in skills is more than profitable for them in these cases.
But don't throw the stick after the axe.
If the behind-the-scenes information is telling the truth and a virtual operator will appear soon, the Czech mobile market may be on the move again.
If one of the operators has agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the OHS to remain impassive in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolnek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov maj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jio Bolohlvek.
We have four versions - with male or female solo singing, a choir performance and an instrumental version.
The vocals are performed by Katesina Knannikova and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Kriek are the authors of the arrangements of the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
The Czech national song is considered one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to the Czech public radio station, he chose to perform solo versions of the singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that the two singers, as well as the choir, had a good diction, so that we understand the words, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
Next year, the Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary.
The song Kde domov muj first resounded in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovaska (Kermesse des Savetiers), an original Czech play by Josef Kajeton Tyl, accompanied by the music of Franti?ek ?kroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first verse naturally became part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
