Public transport (MHD) Prague will introduce, Wednesday, the chip in their ticketing system
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will be recorded in the history of the Prague Transport Agency as the date on which the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, who, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, the latter is accessible for about one hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can purchase a voucher for 30 days or 90 days (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and both have it registered on their smart card at the information points and offices of the Dopravna Podnik (Transport Agency), located at the Muzeum, M?stek, N?dra? Hole?ovice, And?l, Roztyly, Let?
From yesterday, there is also the possibility to buy the coupons by internet on the web pages of the Dopravna podnik: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people took advantage of the service during the morning.
Those who will start using the online store can permanently forget about the ticket counters in the metro stations, where they had until now to tread with impatience in long queues in order to get paper tickets.
Indeed, they will buy their coupon via the internet and it will be registered on their Opencard in one of the thirteen M?stsk? knihovna (municipal libraries).
“In these points of contact, there is a ticket office available to passengers with trained staff, who will help the interested parties with the purchase via the internet and, in addition, will record the coupon they have purchased on their card,” said project spokesman Martin Opatrna.
Next to the libraries, it will also be possible to save the electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, reminiscent of the ticket-composting machines and passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budsjovick, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavsk.
“Today the city has five, but by the end of the year there should be eighty,” added Opatrna.
An automaton will check the coupon instead of the driver
The automatons that will work from tomorrow, are easy to use.
Simply introduce the Opencard smart card and the previously purchased coupon will register itself on the card.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also around the city.
Namely in the suburban trains and the bus lines 300 to 499, which mainly use the inhabitants of the communes of the Central Bohemia to access the capital.
"In the trains integrated in Prague integrated doprava (integrated transports of Prague), the controllers are equipped with card readers, with the help of which they establish the temporary and zonal validity of the coupons;" explained the control of the tickets Filip Drapal of the organization Ropid, which designs the schedules of the public transport Prague.
