The Sudeten demanded a referendum in the United States.
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans demanded that the city be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jiho-esk-v-deck-knihovna (The Scientific Library of Southern Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This stems, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jiho-esk-v-deck-knihovna.
In a letter to the US president, some Germans from the Czech Republic urged the US president not to allow "Cumavsk" (region of forests south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
“We have understood the situation and want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that the American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,” the letter, signed by “People, to whom the fate of the Umava is close to heart,” reads.
Given that the rallying to Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only brutality, attitude without regard, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take in his hands the protectorate of the Umava for now and forever.
“We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a state foreign to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which has in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into consideration the opinion of the quarter of a million inhabitants,” the letter reads.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the “Czech oppressors’ desire for revenge.”
If the president of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naïve, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least to foresee that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some expected that the United States and Great Britain would obtain for the Sudetenland a certain type of autonomy.
Others believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The well-known Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who was born in the town of Budajovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of Seké Budsjovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
“They believed that once they got home, Czech would be good for them,” says Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed, according to him, that, as a result of the Benea Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
You don't think - you pay!
An emotional campaign will attack drivers
The most expensive road safety action in Czech history.
A way of characterizing the emotional media campaign that the Ministry of Transport intends to launch on Wednesday.
The office of the minister Ale?eb?ek believes that it will discourage drivers from dangerous driving behavior.
The $150 million campaign will appear on television, radio, film, the internet and on leaflets.
It should discourage drivers from driving fast and from drinking while driving.
But also remind them to take the belt before starting.
Above all, it wants to touch the consciousness of young drivers, bikers, pedestrians, not to mention professional drivers.
What will appear in the spots?
Especially personal stories that will attack emotions.
This is also reflected in the “bloody” slogan of the entire campaign:
You don't think - you pay!
The phrase "You don't think" is capitalized on the license plate.
Then, in a puddle of blood, there’s the phrase “You’ll pay.”
This must symbolize that one can pay with life a moment of inattention.
The spots will "haunt" the spectators until 2010.
The ministry was inspired by similar campaigns in Anglo-Saxon countries, where images with drastic images of accident victims can be commonly seen.
He believes that this will lead to a decrease in the accident rate and the number of deaths on Czech roads.
The spots were prepared by the agency Euro RSCG.
The strategy of sugar and whip against drivers
“What works with drivers is the sugar and whip system.
For them, sugar is represented, for example, by the fact of saving time, when they grill a red light.
The whip is the threat of a fine or an accident.
Drivers should be reminded of the risks,” says Martin Koon, the transport psychologist at Na Homolce Hospital.
This is how we need information campaigns in the press and especially negative advertisements, believes the psychologist.
Signs warning drivers of danger are already less effective.
"When a static panel that warns of a hazard is installed, it will probably quickly merge with the environment and drivers will not notice it," Koon reported.
Olmert would return in return for peace almost all the occupied territories
Ehud Olmert, the president of Israel’s provisional government, ruled in favor of the return of virtually all the territories occupied in 1967, including the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
