Questions that arise after the accident: Are stewards in the bus illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long-distance bus is forbidden
In the context of the tragic accident of the coach of the company Student Agency near Padua, Italy, arises the question if stewards and passengers can move during the journey inside the coach.
"If we wanted to strictly and formally comply with the law, the activity of a steward is contrary to the law on road traffic," said Karel Hanzelka, a spokesman for the transport ministry.
The accident in question, in which a 22-year-old hostess died, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck who crossed the path of the bus.
The girl was at that time unfortunately sitting next to the driver, in the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she has two other seats at her disposal.
However, the coach can have an accident, or even brake abruptly, also when the steward serves coffee or distributes newspapers.
What matters is whether the coach is under its data sheet equipped with standing seats or not.
If this standing equipment is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
The Student Agency long-distance coaches do not have standing seats; this was confirmed at Aktul.cz by the director of the company Radim Janura.
“This is an issue that we have dealt with with the ministry and, at the beginning, it prohibits any movement of passengers.
Then they cancelled it and we got the passengers to go to the toilet during the ride provided they have their own seat,” he said.
The law ignores the steward.
"There is no one-sided legal interpretation of the steward role - no legal prescription deals with that role.
On the other hand, there are no legal prescriptions prohibiting the carrier from offering services.
The law on road transport knows only the term vehicle catcher; it does not define its rights and duties," Hanzelka added.
Josef Pokorna, the director of the Department of Road Traffic, believes, on the contrary, that the law sufficiently addresses the problem.
"It all depends on whether the bus has permission to offer standing seats in its homologation.
It’s all in there,” he said.
Coaches are divided into urban, where there are standing places and a limited maximum speed, interurban with standing places and a higher authorized speed and long distance coaches without standing place with the highest authorized maximum speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
Just like on the plane, an expert says.
Jaroslav Hoon, an expert at BESIP (road traffic safety) in transport safety, does not see the movement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"In regular traffic, there is no danger. The situation can be compared to that of service in aircraft.
There, too, he is not sure when turbulence will occur and the air hostess can bump into her head.”
Now, in the event that the coach had braked abruptly, the laws of physics would obviously be valid.
In the same way as in an urban bus or in a tram.
The carrier must manage the safety of stewards through internal requirements," he said, and also believes that from the point of view of the law, the problem is not solved.
Janaura is ready to remove these services
Student Agency is the only coach carrier to offer the services of stewards.
He hires two hundred.
Even after this accident, the director does not consider their profession as a risky profession.
"Nevertheless, as soon as I get the impression that this is a risky job, I will remove it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and newspaper at boarding.
It would also reduce costs,” he said.
The safety concern is the reason given to the absence of stewards in his vehicles by the director of the Asiana Alexei Litvine, which ensures, in comparison with SA, a very small number of lines.
"We don't have any hostesses. We've been against it from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end in a fatal accident,” he said, a year ago, at T-den.cz.
A huge tragedy has happened.
A young hostess from the Plzeo region, who had been working for the company for two years, died during the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency stop strip without using a flashing light and it blocked the way to the bus.
The driver of the latter trying to avoid it by means of a sudden maneuver, but he brushed it by his right side.
The two seats reserved for the rest of the stewards were sold.
"In the case of long-distance lines, it is not possible to reserve these places, they are blocked."
The company plans to file a complaint against the truck driver.
For the compensation of the family of the girl, the agency will not wait for the judgment of the court, but as for the financial compensation, it also relies on the culprit.
An amendment to the law?
Not in sight
An amendment to the law, which has been in the process of being drafted for more than a year by a group of thirty experts from the Ministry of Transport, could provide clarification on the trips of the stewards on board the coach.
"However, it has not reached any conclusion on this point.
In fact, she is not too interested in buses, but rather in the points system, the maximum speed on the highway and the use of the mobile phone behind the wheel," says the expert.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of stewards as something that would fundamentally endanger the safety of passengers," Hanzelka concluded, adding that the control of bus safety is under the power of the police and the Office for Safety at Work.
The hopes of the Dusseldorfers rest on Frankfurt.
The big words were not lacking in the letter sent by the WestLB steering committee to the employees of the house.
By a union of the entities of the financial institute of Dusseldorf with the Deka-Bank of Frankfurt, "the central institution of the financial markets of the financial group of Sparkasse" could be constituted, according to the mail made public Monday.
The WestLB would bring a "competence block" coupled with sustainable productivity in such a case.
All in all, such a relationship could be the decisive starting point for further mergers in the banking sector in the Land.
This is what it looks like when an executive committee wants to demonstrate its ability to act in difficult times.
Because the WestLB, injured, is still under strong pressure.
It is not only the European Commission, but also the Federal Financial Services Supervisory Authority that has, only recently, made it clear to the government of the Land of North Rhine-Westphalia that time is running out in the search for a future solution.
However, for some time now - also on the Frankfurt side - there has been talk of a relationship of some kind between Deka Bank, which knows Sparkasse's clients through their investment funds, and WestLB.
Certainly the head of the Deta-Bank Franz Waas has indicated during the presentation of the figures of the semester at the end of August that he does not see any meaning in the merger of the house of the Mainzer Landstrasse with a bank of Land, be it the Helaba or the WestLB.
However, the Board of Directors of the Deka, each half of which is supported by the banks of the Land and by the groups of savings banks, has instructed the Steering Committee to conduct talks with the WestLB for joint business activities.
It could then be the debit of the financial market, or parts of it.
However, the talks have only just begun, it is said in the financial center.
This is not the first time that Deta-Bank, with its 3,000 employees, counts as one of the largest employers in the Frankfurt financial center, comes into play when it comes to the consolidation of the savings bank sector.
In 2003 it was believed for a while that Deta-Bank could merge with the Land Bank of Rhineland Palatinate and Halbab.
Nothing came out of this ternary bouquet.
No sooner had the plans been made public than the government of the Land of Hesse pronounced itself against any participation of the Hellaba in them.
After that, the other two houses didn’t join either.
The Land Bank of Rhineland-Palatinate was instead attached to the Land Bank of Baden-Wuttenberg in Stuttgart.
But there have always been new negotiations on the merger of Deka-Bank with banks in the Land.
Finally, however, Hellaba’s Chairman of the Board, Gunther Merl, opposed any commercial strategy to merge with his bank.
Apart from this, there seems to be a growing sense that the consolidation of the various public sector institutions is particularly urgent.
Now that the election to the Bavarian Parliament has passed, a union of the BayernLB with the Baden-Wuttenberg State Bank could come to fruition first.
For Helaba, this is not particularly good news.
If the pressure on new mergers were to increase, potential partners would gradually slip away.
In the South, it would now be a junior partner, although it has so far resisted the crisis better than the banks of Munich and Stuttgart.
The Hesse-Thuringia savings and transfers group, which owns 85 per cent of Helaba's capital, did, however, lock down any union with WestLB at the beginning of the year.
The NordLB would remain.
Such geo-strategic reflections, however, reflect only one facet.
Another aspect raises the question of how the different business models of each of these banks can fit together.
In June, Merl stated that the decisive question of which business model should ensure the future capacity of the banks in the Land had not yet been resolved by the German grouping of savings banks and credit transfers.
Eventually, a WestLb cutting could take place, cutting which here is obviously not desired.
This is also what is referred to in the letter of the existing Executive Committee: in any case, a "comprehensive solution" would be sought for the institution.
How all this will be put in the same basket with the union of some entities with the Deta-Bank remains to be seen.
