Insomnia Nights for Hypo Real Estate Shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, insisted the Federal Minister of Finance just a few weeks ago.
How lucky that the politician used the word "relatively" and slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared from the crisis movements.
This one actually happened this weekend.
Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), on the side of the DAX, obtains from a consortium of German banks a credit of one billion to protect itself from the turbulence of the markets.
A person in the confidence of the situation told Reuters on Monday that the aid credits are issued up to 35 billion euros.
The Hypo Real Estate would now have to pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes as much from private banks as from public law banks.
In the background, it is the daughter company Depfa that bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible since because of distrust towards the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's liquidity reserve had been reduced by 95 percent to 2.37 million euros, while the equity rate had also declined slightly from 1.6 percent to 1.45 percent.
Current and net profits from financial transactions were, compared to the same period the previous year, zero, profits from the allocation of specified receivables and securities as well as the termination of provisions in credit transactions had fallen by more than 70 percent to 5 million euros.
And it was only thanks to the large profits from the reimbursement of downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as from the repayment of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for Konzern's companies that the shortfall in earnings of about 16 percent turned out to be moderate.
After its privatization in 1990, the former state financier had initially speculated badly on industrial real estate loans, which had then been filialized to the bank Aareal.
Because conventional state financing was not profitable enough, Depfa was then more intensely involved in infrastructure projects and in the financing of joint projects between private and state investors (Private-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the daughter company, the Hypo Real Estate must make depreciations which should have on the calculation of the gains and losses of the group an essential material effect which remains nevertheless rather vague.
The fact is that the dividends have been amputated.
By 2007, they had been cut to two-thirds.
Since the acquisition of Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has been a highly important state and infrastructure investor.
It is stronger than other institutions dependent on refinancing on the interbank market since it has no customer deposits.
With the collapse of investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of loans between banks has again dried up considerably, as banks have accumulated their liquidity.
The Hypo Real Estate needs annually for a part - about 50 billion euros - of all the credits of the Depfa of a medium short-term refinancing.
According to a statement from the Hypo Real Estate, the group's financing need is covered with medium-term credit and the company protected from the influence of the international financial markets largely out of working condition at the moment.
Other sources say the refinancing would be secured through the funds until the end of 2009.
HRE Executive Chairman Georg Funke said the Hypo Real Estate group should no longer have to resort to financial markets in the medium term.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Institution for the Supervision of Financial Services (Bafin) assume that the Hypo Real Group's capacity in the market is now assured.
The bank’s shareholders and creditors can only hope so.
However, given the dynamics and unaccountability of the crisis, there is no certainty.
Moreover, it is not unthinkable that funding should not be used to its full extent.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the bank is, according to the latest statements, still on the verge of insolvency late Sunday evening, this temporary rescue will not succeed in reassuring minds either.
The share price fell from 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are doing particularly well.
While debts in the first place have barely moved, the prices of second-rate loans are declining.
The most affected are, of course, the investment funds of the former daughter-company W rttemberg Hypo and those that have a lifespan beyond 2009.
The bonds of Hypo Real Estate Bank previously seemed to be an alternative speculative investment, now their value must be considered as dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the very institute that brought the crisis into the institution by the acquisition of the bank Depfa.
As long as the issuing institutions, governments and less affected commercial banks are still ready to support the system, it can be assumed that the arrears will be resolved over time.
Or what no one dares hope will happen right now – that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of the renewed noises of partial nationalization, the probability that approached security has now become a mere well-founded hope.
This should reserve sleepless nights above all for long-term creditors on whether they should part with their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they have drawn a line on to build a carry-over of losses for the next few years on the next capital income tax of stock gains automatically levied.
