Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our voluble nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impute them to others than to ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from primitive activities are born in the regions of the corporeal sensation of the Cortex and the brainstem, just like Jaak Pankseep, who however focuses more on the brainstem.
As this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could quite participate in transverse sensations of any kind.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe it to be unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears as fear in both humans and rats is likely to be felt as such in both cases: how can we check if rats and humans feel the same way when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach flees from danger, but if he feels fear?
