"I photograph the master out of the scene to capture elements of his character" G?nther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of the man or the woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these moments unknown to the general public, where one discovers to intimate gestures and stolen looks of artists who do not care to go on stage.
In "Flamenco - people" the German G?nther Bauer mixes the theatricality of some stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer takes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Flemish Month of Photography, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater each day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists do not take photos on stage.
They have a personality and character of their own.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera moments of personality of flamenco stars."
With the festival "Song of the Mines", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
They are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, recall classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about dance or singing itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the public with his art.
The search for the essentials and magic has been the constant of this work that we present these days at the El Fot?mata gallery.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
The project turned into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book collecting portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves photographing people's portraits, getting to know them and being able to enter their lives for a more or less long time.
I believe that in photography portraiture is the most difficult genre.
You are in front of people, characters that sometimes you do not know or who leave you only a few minutes to take a picture.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true.”
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is on display at the El Fotomata Gallery, located at number 20 of the rue de la Mata (street parallel to the Peopleraie d'Hercule) which will be open until October 16th.
