"Sangre de Mayo", the daring bet of Garci
Inspired by the stories of Benito Pérez Galdus, José Luis Garci recreates the famous battle of the Spanish against the French in "Sangre de mayo", which is the most ambitious film of his filmography with nearly 15 million euros in budget.
The filmmaker tried "to stage the many characters and illustrate the social analysis" that he has always admired in the work of the famous novelist, he explained today during the presentation of the film, with Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarria at the head of the long list of actors.
The more than two-and-a-half-hour film, "Sangre de mayo" will be released in theaters next Friday, which will then become a TV series for Telemadrid of more than four hours.
José Luis Garci, a great admirer of Galdis’s literature, claims to have realized with this filming “a childhood dream” thanks to Esperanza Aguirre, who commissioned him, three years ago, to shoot a commemorative film for the two hundred years of Madrid’s 2nd May, something he always accepted when the story stuck to national historical facts.
The 15 million euros provided by the Commune of Madrid constitute for Garci a "unique opportunity" to reproduce with the appropriate decorations and clothing the atmosphere of "a Spain that has been mistaken leader for the fight, since, the struggle for independence has led the people to rebellions under the reign of Ferdinand VII", he pointed out.
But the filmmaker regrets not having obtained funding as for the films "Captain Alatriste" or "Ghosts of Goya" - more than double that obtained for "Sangre de mayo" - because he could not shoot a few scenes written in a script signed by Horacio Valcarcel, with whom he collaborated during almost all his career.
The filmmaker of "Volver a empezar" has influenced his usual way of working, on the staging of actors, with whom he is used to rehearse before starting the shooting and to whom he does not cast, since it seems "humiliating" to him and considers that "the role of the filmmaker is to go to the theater and the cinema to keep informed".
Many actors in "Sangre de mayo" rehearse in front of the camera, such as Miguel Renlan, Carlos Larranaga or Fernando Guillén Cuervo.
Four-time Oscar contender (he won one), Garci considers that the three candidate films that represent Spain this year at the Hollywood Academy, “Sangre de mayo,” “Seven French pool tables” and finally the winner, “The Blind Sunflowers,” are not representative of the young Spanish cinema, “that would deserve to be better known,” he said.
With this movie Garci does not expect a price.
“At first you think you’re working for posterity, then you realize that you’re only working for prosperity, and now you’re just making an extra movie,” Garci says after more than 30 years of professional career.
