Alcohol abusers at the wheel will have to install the 'alcolock' system
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative sanctions for alcohol, to have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents starting the vehicle in a state of drunkenness, or if he does not blow.
The initiative was already announced last June and it is now reflected in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered as a pilot project that will last one year.
Its purpose is to reintegrate the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State in charge of road safety but also the Directorate General of Road Safety and the Technological Institute Foundation for Motor Vehicle Safety will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for having driven in a drunken state more than once, takes the car back.
The alcolock would avoid this since it is a system plugged into the vehicle that measures the alcohol level in the breath and prevents starting the vehicle if the driver does not blow before; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than allowed.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is the responsibility of the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced up to 65% of infringements during the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save the lives of 115 people every year.
This only applies to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with such behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And facilitate its implementation, since the legal reform can be done by ordinary means but, however, the reform done by criminal means requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative of the Spanish Socialist Party which proposes to install this system in school buses as it was done in France.
