Interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, he regained the public trust that had been seriously shaken by the tainted blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood supply managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service was contaminated with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and public outrage, the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations for the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was slow to table his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and Canadian Blood Services to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field during the years that followed, we regained the public's trust," she says before proudly affirming that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its creation on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, there were numerous cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the one that has held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
“And we didn’t know at all whether this disease could be transmitted through blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when it is not known and a serious disease can result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
However, a few years ago, it was shown beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that we applied made sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for HIV testing appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NATs), which make it possible to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have made it possible to shorten the silent period, which extends between when the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period was reduced to less than one week.
This has substantially reduced the risk of unknowingly infecting some donors and not being able to detect them.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
“In other words, it means we’ll have to distribute 12 million blood products before someone is infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I think we can now feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to regain health," said Héma-Québec's CEO.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Just last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide a sufficient supply.
“Needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a refill of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population is also having an impact on the blood donor network, which on average accounts for only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate blood.
Any healthy person 18 years of age or older who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a malaria-affected country, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But we need to renew the members of this donor network as they get older and can no longer donate blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become a regular donor.
Today’s life is so frantic, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,” laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for burn victims.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is packed with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
A few weeks ago, we celebrated the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample and we plan to take more than a thousand a year.
We should start offering them for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
