In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice-President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Pursuing Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has filed a six million libel suit against three authors and a small penniless publishing house in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation lawsuits, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to lead to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money to prepare their defence and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mining industry.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition and scare anyone who dares to look again at the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in front of public opinion that she should have presented her view of the facts.
Unlike many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally conducted through the exchange of ideas and not by batons.
So it was enough for the mining company to open its books, its files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold appears to be untrusting to public opinion and dismisses petitions and letters in support of Black Canada's authors.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both ask for a "public" debate while disregarding the opinions of that same public?
In the Vice-President's world, it seems that this word refers only to the lawyers who are well paid and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public who support Black Canada's authors and publishers does so primarily because they reject the brutal way of mining.
This audience is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a gag order (pursuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a formal notice against the authors of Black Canada asking them to stop using this term ...).
Beyond Mr. Garver’s surreal discourse, Barrick Gold’s pursuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, en bloc, the right to the citation of credible sources and to the debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss issues that are displeasing to the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate pursuit makes it clear that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for academia, as well as for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street rescue operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally came to an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months still needs to be endorsed by both houses of Congress.
It includes: better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right of control over the salaries paid to the managers of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Representative at the negotiating table Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
“We have made great strides toward a deal that will be effective in the markets,” said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
“Everything has been done in a way that shields the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“That’s the fundamental point: If we don’t do that, the trauma, chaos and disruption to the everyday lives of Americans will be immense,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned into a sprint in the last hours for fear of the effect that a new failure would cause on the mood of investors.
The deadline was the opening of the markets this morning.
Associated late in the negotiations, the two candidates in the US presidential election were rather favorable to the agreement, without failing to express however their dissatisfaction that one is forced to arrive at this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has attributed the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including the one to allow homeowners to keep their homes and the one on the salaries of executives of companies rescued by the state.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to celebrate.
But these measures are necessary,” he said on American television.
Asked on another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The outline I read [shows] that it's something we're all going to have to digest and we're going to be able to move forward with.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to redeem with taxpayer money the bad debts, risky assets and unsaleable US financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages before spreading to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to a liquidity freeze and the disbandment of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of elected Republicans who blew up the first draft of the agreement last week.
It is believed to have broken this deadlock since Democrats agreed that some “toxic” assets of troubled companies are only insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to round the corners for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to assume losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion to which can be added another 100 billion if the president deems it necessary.
Another $350 billion is expected to be approved by another congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get stakes in the rescued companies that will earn him dividends in case of profit and that he can resell when the turmoil is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay foreclosure procedures for homes attached to mortgages covered by this plan, as well as set limits on compensation and severance payments to executives of affected businesses.
The architects of the plan would like to see it put to the vote in the House of Representatives today, and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Indeed, voices continued to speak out yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camp.
“Obviously Washington doesn’t hear you,” Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told voters.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not to take advantage of taxpayers.”
Leader of a small group in Congress dubbed “the caucus of skeptics,” Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to tell us: Congress is being asked not to hurry and to carefully examine the way forward,” he said.
At the same time, in Europe, there was again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the banking group Fortis for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was giving up on acquiring its competitor in the middle of a shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of Europe’s 20 largest banks and 10 largest insurers.
“This is not lost money,” Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In exchange, we get back a voting right in the bank and influence.
This is precisely something that savers and households now appreciate as times look uncertain.”
Meanwhile, across the Channel, the British government appeared to be nationalizing another bank battered by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all outstanding loans at Bradford and Bringley Bank, including more than 41 billion (US 75.5 billion) of mortgage loans.
The Spanish bank Santander said yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
Its beauty in the eyes of azure was for a long time its asset card, some will say its weakness.
Had he freed himself from the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with a charming smile?
Yes and no.
His modesty, his sensitivity and a talent that flowed from source will also have distanced him from the register of power that gives birth to the true sacred monsters.
But what a great long-distance runner!
Paul Newman, who died Friday at age 83 from lung cancer at his Connecticut ranch, remains one of the last icons of American cinema of the booming years.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of whom he was for a long time a kind of rival on the screen, more cautious in his play, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the bursting of dramatic conventions.
Mixed bloods often make beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925 to a German Jewish father and a Hungarian mother.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, the ultimate brand of quality.
Because in him a whole country in love with the self-made man, the fighter of the Pacific war, wounded in combat, who in the early 50s studied drama at Yale and then attended the Actor's Studio in New York, before triumphing in theater, television, soon in cinema.
The same man who campaigned for civil rights was also the second-placed driver at the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans, dubbed a sex symbol, though a member of a model couple formed since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
Also disappear with him the shadows of this secret star, discreet, committed, allergic to the bursts of show business, whose riddle we have not quite cracked.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the word.
The disappearance of Paul Newman has made moviegoers dizzy this weekend, as his big roles collide on the black screen of memories.
More than half a century of a seventh American art in perpetual mutation scrolls through it.
Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), the young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on a Burning Roof adapted from Tennessee Williams in 1958.
Closer to us (1990), we evoke his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage that did not fulfill all his promises.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
This boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role intended for James Dean, reprised after his death, who really launched Newman in 1956.
This sympathetic thug in the brilliant The Sting (L'Arnaque), Oscar for best film in 1973.
Bitter billiards player and vengeful in Robert Rossen's The Hustler (1961), he will reprise the character on Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earned him his only Oscar out of nine nominations in 1987.
That face through the ages was him.
Just him again.
Times are moving through his journey.
The young people know him mainly through the cult Slap Shot of George Roy Hill (1977), in Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen brothers.
With a last role as the godfather of the Irish Mafia in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes in 2003, the loop was complete.
Contrary to several film legends who soon let go of the profession, Newman remained in the saddle for a long time, while denouncing Hollywood, its golds, its pomp and its concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered it, not without humor, "as a living challenge to "underplaying" judging his performances too supported.
The profession has not always been tender for the beautiful Paul Newman to whom the roles fell for a long time all cooked in the beak.
He played, however, less often the young first than the marginalized: neurotics, alcoholics, bastards or desperate, whose perfect features reflected the drifts and revolts.
As a director, Newman revealed poorly known facets of his true modest sensibility.
Her Rachel, Rachel, in 1968 (after the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the lead role, drew a fine female portrait of melancholy.
He who lost his son Scott by overdose dedicated his film Harry and Son in 1984, a work of modesty and sadness.
Among the rain of tributes yesterday on Newman, his great friend and former companion in arms Robert Redford (they had played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said, very saddened: "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of existence are vibrant traits of the missing actor.
Beyond his legendary career, also fades a great activist for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a protester of the excesses of Hollywood.
We will have seen a lot of his dinette sitting on jars of dressing, sauces, biscuits and other foods, judging the process to be quite bad taste, although gag at first.
The profits from these sales were nevertheless paid to his Foundation for Children in Trouble.
Newman, rather than sit on his myth, will have committed himself to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter containing these phrases: "Always and to the end, your father was incredibly grateful for his good star.
It was a privilege to be here.”
And a privilege for us to have followed the path of such a lucid and generous American artist.
Model citizen, in sum and in addition.
What could Zuschlag & Compagnie do in their invoice factory?
Soon, on 8 October, the hearings relating to the ongoing criminal proceedings will begin, against Jonos Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are charged with fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, resulting in particularly significant damage. Other charges have been brought against them, such as forgery and the use of forgery.
According to the prosecutor's office, the money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money of the state and the municipalities, about 65 million HUF in total, went on the one hand into the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other hand, into the pockets of certain people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to receive money from subsidies obtained by issuing bills of costs, behind which no actual benefits were provided and thus, the associations never met their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they procured invoice books at the market in Jazsefvros, while they manufactured the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that were going to appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by Istvan Lados, at the request of Jonos Zuschlag.
According to the testimony of the latter, he had to locate pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they realized the other invoices that they would introduce, among others, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by Istvin Lados and his accomplice Andrus Ari, who, according to our information, was mainly involved in drafting the files necessary to obtain the subsidies.
During a "tracking circuit", one of Lados's choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place ensured the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyes-let.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
In the same way, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up in the name of the Jobb J?v?ért foundation, which would later be called Egy?tt a Harmadik Évezredért, was riddled with errors of form and substance.
One pension in Badacsonytomaj actually had only three rooms, and a maximum of ten people could spend the night there, yet the bill mentioned one hundred and thirty guests.
The over-invented invoice issuers also fell into overdrive when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. In their accounts, neither Jobb Jov ért nor the Hopp name appeared, according to the information given to the prosecutor.
The company's manager, Gyuza Farkas, told hvg.hu that when the prosecutor's office summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew, right away, that they were fake documents.
"Our company name and our tax number were placed in a wrong place on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that according to the bill, a hundred people stayed there, did not stick either, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have as much room.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
The zealous invoice issuers also did not inquire about Budapest's travel agencies, which are part of their choice, but only organise trips abroad, so naively they indicated trips to Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which also goes against the agency's accounting practices.
Moreover, as it appeared during the survey, they also added VAT on these documents, while the services concerning travel activities, whose destination is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices drawn up in the name of the Hotel Révf-l-p to Jobb J-v-ert was incorrect, since the company's services do not support a 25% VAT as indicated, but a 15% VAT. In addition, the hotel's employees only issue printed invoices, while the fakes were written by hand.
The investigation of the prosecutor's office reveals that the "issuers" also committed errors by mentioning as a service the transport of goods by road, which the company issuing the invoices could not exercise, since its profile was the investment advice.
In addition, it is also for defects of form, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued to the order of Egyatt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapattviny, of XXI.
As in the case of the company Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehért sports course, both of which deny being the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
Nor did the counterfeiters pay attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., based in Nyaregyhza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) when the group of Fiatal Vorosért Egyeslet was supposed to have a meal at their home, which is why, according to our information, the liquidator of the company denies having issued this invoice.
Invoices deliberately drawn up
Another category of invoice issuers is that of those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictitious invoices.
At the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifj - Szocialist -k consortium, the Esély Budapestért Alap -tv -ny Foundation has issued an invoice to the Egy -tt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért for a sum of HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the manager of Collab Kft. was forced to issue false invoices by one of the defendants, Ludovic Gyorfi.
Similarly, it cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently under liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices to the Jobb Foundation, the Atlasz Egyeslet association and the Vorsfeny Egyeslet association, for an amount of approximately HUF 5 million, but behind which no benefit was actually provided.
No financial movement took place either, since the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but this, the organizations did avoid mentioning it in their accounts.
The next category of companies issuing invoices is that of companies directly related to the accused.
For example, the administrative representative of the managing director of Delta Trie Kft., dealing in the trade of fuel and motor vehicles, whose head office was in Budapest but where it could not be found, was Ivan Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of IT equipment, amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, the equipment was purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of this company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Ivan Kubatov also sent documents related to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices to the companies Atlasz, Hoppa and Egyatt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapitvany, and that he pocketed their counter value.
It was precisely at the request of Ivan Kubatov that Romanian masons created the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
