Kubatov donated 15 invoices issued by the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trio, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade to organizations for a value of HUF 14.2 million.
Prosecutors believed that 10% of the sums indicated on the invoices as well as VAT went into Kubatov’s pocket.
The man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to draw up fictitious invoices that were used in the Biztos Pont grant application.
In January 2006, the Association Y-Generaci? and Sz?vetség a Modern Magyarorsz?gért applied for a subsidy from the public utility of the Socialist Party, T?ncsics Mih?ly Alap?tv?ny (TMA).
They obtained this grant for an amount of twice HUF 500,000, but these amounts were not used for the purposes indicated in the application.
To avoid this, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were presented to the TMA.
Moreover, it is these invoices that were found during the search carried out in the office of Orpud Kemecsei, at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the defendants will report on the method of manufacturing the invoices, as they had done before the prosecutor's office.
What could be really interesting would be that the main defendant, Jonos Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil on the whole story.
So far, his confessions are not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to tell the smallest details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or perhaps the Socialists would have reached an agreement that in exchange for the reimbursement of a large part of the fifty million HUF, Zusi would wear the hat alone.
Today, the latter is probably vexed, since applications for his placement under house arrest, on the basis of a reduction in his conditions of detention, are continually falling into the ear of a deaf person.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and the perpetrators of unrepairable economic crimes, walk freely or at least wait in their own homes for the end of the proceedings.
The psychology of overbidding: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Neurology and economics researchers at New York University have been able to uncover the neurological and economic underpinnings of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research has attempted to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group took part in a fun auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the overbidding of a third, the whole under the brainstem, called striatum, moved intensively when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the nervous system's "self-stimulation" mechanism.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight in front of the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the members of this group of researchers pursued financial surveillance analyses.
During these, three groups were overbidding a partner, under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out the winner of the game, then they would receive an additional $15, as a reward.
While the third group received the $15 before the auction, the group members also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is, in fact, that the emphasis was on victory in one group, while the emphasis was on failure in the other.
By thus proving the neurologists’ hypothesis, the members of the players’ team “against failure” were willing to bets higher than those made by the control group and the group “for victory”.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by leading, now, to a third explanation." - found Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When should I see a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
There are an estimated one hundred thousand patients with hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven thousand are receiving treatment, due to the fact that often patients do not know they are carrying the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through the blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
In any case, it is recommended for travellers to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated foods, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, upset stomach and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stool becomes lighter and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, one million people die each year from the most serious form of hepatitis B, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis.
The main cause is that it is estimated that only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know they have the virus, because the pathogenic gene deviously destroys liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms do not appear until after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users, and tattooed people.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its goal is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God feel less pain?
According to the results of recent research, religious belief would function as a kind of analgesic, which would already have helped to make the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British newspaper Telegraph published an article according to which researchers from the University of Oxford carried out an interesting experiment by analyzing at what level belief in God could influence human pain tolerance.
As part of this bizarre experiment, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshock, while each of them observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments, in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More precisely, the experiment proceeds in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing electroshock is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at two paintings in a sustained way, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the Ermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers behind this experiment hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, focused on its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time, received 20 electroshocks in four parts succeeding each other, while looking at either the religious theme painting or the more general theme painting.
Catholics said that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe", like someone who was "taken care of" and they "calmed down, and peace invaded them".
At the sight of the painting of religious themes, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at the work of Leonardo.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that one can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in atheists, provided one finds the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image that they react to very positively, such as a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, praised the results of this research.
“The practice of faith should change and in many cases, actually changes our personality,” Wright added.
After these excellent results, there remains only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if one shows to the believers a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would the sight of a higher quality Virgin Mary cause better results?
You are what you reveal about yourself.
On its tenth anniversary, Google says it can be found in the back of people’s pockets just like the sky above their heads. It knows where they spent their holidays, what specialists they consult and what their interests are.
But that’s not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, who is one of the most influential people in society.
While when it comes to skeptics drawing a parallel with Orwell’s horror vision, they just don’t see the bulk of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main ambition is to gather even more information about its users. This is necessary so that the founders of Google can meet their initial goal which sounded like: "Let's collect all the world's information in one system!"
According to the Google executive interviewed, after ten years of a global shakeup, they are still only at the beginning of their goals of being able to process all the information.
Schmidt responded that he would like Google to be able to answer questions like “What could I do tomorrow?” or “What would work best for me?” However, software will only be able to answer this kind of question, simple at first glance, when they know enough about users.
It is not perfectly clear to all Internet users that the words used during searches on the Internet, the IP address of the computer that launches the search and the pages consulted by interested persons are precisely listed.
Through the Personalized Search program launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own search history and can view what they searched for, what they clicked on. Through this, in the long run, Recommendations, a program based on the same logic, will be able to give much more personalized answers, and will submit products and services to us based on our previous statements and saved preferences.
What happens if someone uses my data against me, if they look at what my job is? ask users, who are worried about Google’s information monopoly.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can arouse fear, and it is not remorse, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or possibly revolt against power that can arouse a counter-reaction among Internet users.
It is, however, a confirmed fact that the terms sought are not only recorded, but in justified cases, they are transmitted to a third party, and in this kind of legal case, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most resounding example of recent times is probably the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google transmitted to the Brazilian government the information it had collected on the public page called Orkut, thus allowing identification.
Internet users concerned about human rights were able to breathe a sigh of relief last May, when Google, arming itself with the electronic legal protection agency EFF, proved its right in court before the FBI. According to the judgment rendered, in the future, Google will still not be able to be forced by any of the points of the constitution to disclose information on the secret request of the FBI, of any kind whatsoever.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms that it had won over the strengthening of the Child Protection Act, passed several years earlier. But in the end, it failed to obtain the lists of searches of private users, nor the entire list of websites and keywords of the past two months.)
Google’s judgment is therefore quite contradictory: it is criticized by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think that their private sphere and their private domain suffer when they start using Google services, and therefore they attack them in the spirit of revolt that is manifested against multinational companies proud of their conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its “savages” bringing together enthusiasts, activists and computer users who appear in many countries see Google as the next generation of big companies, the “connected corporation”, as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, cataloged as an invader of the world because of Windows, even if both are fighting for the same goal.
This can be explained by the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for identification code, does not ask for money for its applications. The document code and the package of programs, continuously refreshed, has a much more accessible effect, younger and cooler, in the face of the practice of the official giant of the software.
The reason may also be that geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between human rights and the Internet, and what the Web 2.0, the most proclaimed keyword of recent years, pulls right behind it.
Indeed, Web 2.0 is not about anything other than collaboration, than the fact that we intentionally leave traces behind us, and that we use the communication channels available to us, and while the dimension of these changes one by one, the essential remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young person, in general, can keep a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link these to other services, such as Twinter, or last.fm, listing his musical habits. Then, he can link these to a tracking system, like FriendFeed or Blip.fm. These young people can also keep blogs, in which automatically appear their most recent photo galleries on Picaslick.
While we can read many examples, such as that of the girlfriend who easily understands at the sight of the photos of the morning, taken by the circle of mutual friends, with whom his infidel friend spent the evening, or that of the company that fired one of its employees, just for the sincere opinions that he wrote on his blog about top management, we can be on one thing: the term of our privacy is totally to reconsider.
The one who lives an online life, is made up of what he shows himself, and this is how one can define the principle hiding behind the behavior of today's young people.
He wants to hide something, or at least, wants to try to circumvent Google’s monopoly, can do it (starting, for example, with Scroogle, using the Google search system, but, at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
The number of people who deliberately do not register on public pages so that it is not possible to find them, is not the least. Google online services, including word processing, image processing, reading information can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not attached to huge server parks and do not assemble our best profile, which has existed until today.
Public opinion is waiting, without really hiding it, for the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
The company, with its current value of $156 billion, is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion).Adwords/AdSense ad domains threaten ad agency revenue, while services introduced at an increasing speed cause serious migraines not only to Microsoft, but to many other computer program creators.
However, critical observers find, alongside all this, contradictions with worrying effects: for example, the top management of the company refused, in its entirety, the protests of the employees, after it has doubled the price of the kindergarten company and after the company has found too expensive the multiple restoration daily, taken at any time.
According to one of the company's internal rules, the new services are not announced only when they can be used. What is sure is that in the coming months and years, they will move the world on new points. While some think that the project of scanning and archiving books and magazines from Google is taking such important dimensions that the company will soon find itself facing our medical problems in the United States.
The fact that Google is building a genetic database can give a good raw material to the next generation of science fiction writers. The famous Cory Doctorow's novel, written with Orwellian halftones, describes the future in which a man could be approached in an amazing way just through Google's data.
