The Warsaw Stock Exchange makes a proposal for the acquisition of the Prague Stock Exchange
The Warsaw Stock Exchange has offered two hundred million euros, about five billion Czech crowns, for the purchase of 100% of the stock package of the Prague Stock Exchange.
Ludwik Sobolewski, the chairman of the Warsaw Stock Exchange, confirmed this proposal that the Poles made despite the fact that previously the Czechs excluded the Warsaw Stock Exchange from the circle of potential new owners of the Prague Stock Exchange.
The reason for this exclusion is that the Warsaw Stock Exchange is in the hands of the state.
99% of the shares are in the hands of the Polish state, which wants to separate more than 60% of its shares in a few months of activity.
According to the Czech business daily E15, the Polish proposal represents the highest bid to buy the Prague stock exchange so far.
According to the Czech press, the Vienna Stock Exchange, the Transatlantic Stock Exchange Nasdaq, the Stock Exchange of New York, the London Stock Exchange and the Deutsche Boerse have made an offer so far.
Petr Koblic, the director of the Prague Stock Exchange, said last week that among the interested parties, the Warsaw Stock Exchange would be the least good new owner, and did not rule out the fact that it could result in the disappearance of the Prague Stock Exchange in the future.
The value of the Prague stock exchange is estimated between 5 and 10 billion Czech crowns by market specialists.
On the basis of an agreement between the shareholders, some 90% of the papers would be sold.
The largest owner of the Prague stock exchange is the investment bank Patria Finance, with about 25 percent stakes, followed by the 14.7 percent of the bank Cesk . Sporitelna and the Tiger Holding Four S. a.r.l. with 13.5 percent.
