Intelligent car mimics drone theft
What method would be better for developing technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if not the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
Like, for example, the bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, held in Japan, buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the initial strategic idea, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired, BR23C-type, self-robotized control system, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval in shape, which in reality, looks very much like our secure protective shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development and technological public relations department of the brand.
The bee’s faceted eye plays a vital role, as it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, engineers approached the idea of the laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance maneuver right away.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it by a sufficient angle to avoid collision.
Unlike any current system, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
“If it wasn’t that way, the mini-auto robot wouldn’t be able to react fast enough to avoid the obstacle,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process should reflect what the bee is doing to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that the bees possess to avoid the other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotary movement, the acceleration as well as the slowing down as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini robot self.
The BR23C uses polymeric Lithium batteries that are lighter and have a larger energy concentrate, making their lifespan longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not data processing, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism has to process only a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don't need memory with gigabyte capacity, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology for instant avoidance, and Nissan estimates that this system will enter mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles in his path.
We even gave a name to the overpriced baby
The written version of the $700 billion economic bailout, aimed at buying back the banks’ dubious loans, and to be used in installments, is ready.
In the first round, half of that money will be spent.
Reuters reports that in new debates lasting until after midnight on Saturday, local time on the east coast, congressional leaders have agreed on the days-and-days-old controversies surrounding the $700 billion bailout package.
“We’ve taken a serious step forward,” said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic president of the American House of Representatives, who said all that’s left to do is put the agreements on paper.
The compromise, born from the plan, is supported by the two presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said in commenting on the results of the compromise that the program will work and will be effective, however other measures have yet to be implemented. According to Pelosi, there is no question here of saving Wall Street, but of turning the wheels of the economy in the other direction.
The written version of the plan was made public ahead of the opening of Asian markets on Sunday evening at 8 p.m. local time in Washington (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m., according to Central European local time), but did not cause a dramatic rise in the stock markets.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill that meets the name of the emergency economic stabilization law of 2008.
On Saturday night, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, and then the White House also welcomed the news of the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress made tonight, and we greatly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
Moreover, the program diverges from the initial proposal made by the Bush administration, which stated that the $700 billion must be spent in one go, for the repurchase of securities on doubtful credits.
From now on, up to half of the $700 billion can be spent. The first $250 billion will be issued immediately after the law is passed by Congress, probably on Monday. This first amount will be used by the Secretary of the Treasury to buy bad loans from banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the discretion of the President.
The program will be overseen by an independent body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also take part.
The spending of the second half of the $700 billion depends on a new congressional order.
Under the law, the Treasury Secretariat will be able to put in place a combined strategy: it will be able, at the same time, to buy bad debts, securities relating to bad mortgages and mortgages, as well as other types of "toxic" debts.
The competent persons of the Ministry have stated that the redemptions can take place in the context of an auction, but also directly.
The rule gives the companies concerned the opportunity to take part in an insurance program, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools that give rise to the concerns, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson said the law provides the necessary tools to spend $700 billion on the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it is the extensive redemption of doubtful debts, their insurance, or to avoid the risk of the system leading to the collapse of one or the other major financial institution.
"We will make the necessary arrangements, to be ready for law enforcement, as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the other hand, bank executives in bad shape and waiting for state aid can expect that their severance payments, simply called golden parachutes across the Atlantic, will be capped by the government.
The salary cap is only mentioned in specific cases, and the limitations depend on how the Treasury Secretariat offers assistance to the business.
The capping principle means that if the Treasury Secretariat buys back through an auction, they will levy a tax surplus on the golden parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Directly after the bad loans are redeemed, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to the executives is not exaggerated.
In order for the image to be complete, it must still be added that the existing golden parachutes are not modified. The cap concerns only the new contracts, this to motivate participation in the plan.
This is the first time in U.S. history that legal caps will be in place on CEO pay - said the chairman of the House of Representatives Financial Benefits Committee, Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the State acquires the right to acquire shares in the banks participating in the plan, thereby reducing the risk of taxpayers, since they can even win in the case as soon as the economy and with it the rescued banks fall on their feet.
The bill says that in the next five years, the president must introduce a proposal to Congress that will rule on how the losses are going to be returned to taxpayers, from the financial sector.
On both sides, of course, there were those who expressed their doubts about this plan.
That’s not why American citizens mandated us, this doesn’t protect taxpayer dollars,” said California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa.
His Democratic colleague from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, believes that it is the same people who are pressing for action, as those responsible for the Wall Street collapse.
Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - reports the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices were up 1.1 percent from July 2008, while compared to a year earlier, they were down 3.9 percent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial selling prices increased only to a lesser extent: by 0.1 per cent, compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors were up only a tiny 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was seen in the leather goods and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8%), with first, bag and belt manufacturing with a monthly increase of 4.6%, then shoe production with a monthly increase of 2.5%.
Higher prices for plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly price increase in the chemical and chemical manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in the oil processing (1.4 per cent), electrical machinery and appliance manufacturing (0.9 per cent) and a minimal increase in the wood processing (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry saw an increase, ranging from 0.2 per cent to 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, representing a significant weight in domestic industrial operations, prices increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, oil processing sector prices saw the most significant increase (32.4 percent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices have increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices have increased by 11 per cent.
Price decreases occurred in the textile and textile products production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
Across the processing industry, prices have increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7 per cent higher than in the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and by sector allocation, in August, the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was in the profit-making sectors.
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials production sectors for further processing showed no change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and materials production sectors for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-generating sectors, inflation was measured at 1.4 per cent.
The export sales prices of the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they suffered a drop of 3.9 percent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment weakened by 1.7 per cent against the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it strengthened by 7.5 per cent against the euro and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
