Mp3 player pointed at, they put at risk the hearing.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent damage to the hearing.
This is what the European Commission announced, which, in a statement released in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unexpected and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific report - we read in the note - it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music at full volume using portable musical devices, for more than one hour per day and week, risk a permanent loss of hearing ability."
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at full volume, may unknowingly damage their hearing irreparably,” Kuneva said.
"According to the scientific data - continues the manager Ue - this is a clear risk and we have to react quickly.
What matters most is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public domain.
We must also re-examine existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can keep up with new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"Scientists confirm that there are good reasons for concern, and that the European Commission will now discuss with Member States and other interested parties what measures could possibly be adopted to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these data using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The Scientific Committee Ue points out that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the limits currently in force relating to the maximum noise level allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods, risk permanent loss of hearing ability after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
