Elites in danger.
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the $700 billion bailout approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is indeed the New York Times of yesterday that confirms it communicating that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions as well as to the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and to the world of finance, powerful especially in the states of the Center and the South.
The soul, precisely, which has been despotically felt with the vote I was talking about at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is only one example of the changes, the big changes that the current economic earthquake is already announcing or letting run: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not only here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena that have been hatched for some time, to such an extent that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the double sovereign-state category, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which obviously have close relations with foreign countries, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families who live in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for who governs it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only here national.
Political internationalisation seems to be out of the question, or else it has little to say: the obvious proof is provided by the European Union, which, as usual, cannot decide any common political line between the various interests and between the various national strategies.
And so, it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all an affection for credits: when you go through a difficult period, it is only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also possess the necessary means and legitimization to use them: two resources of inestimable value, elements that no market or international organization will ever be able to dispose of in a similar way.
This new emphasis of the nation-state crisis is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-greater importance that more recent economic developments tend to attribute to a factor rather related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of ever more sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at one stroke that our future will have to settle its accounts more and more with the rather unmaterial things like water, crops, oil.
Things which can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth, but which are absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than the one who is not, that is, the one who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shade.
And moreover, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even disturbing: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a sense of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in a growing number of Western countries.
Thus the conviction of the various classes increases even more, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be always more foreign to the opinions of the majorities.
In short, the demand for leadership, in an underground way, feeds a powerful and branched movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised electoral "revolts" or, alternatively, in the collective mood changes of recent times, from the conservative ascent in Austria Bavaria, to the fall of Labour in Great Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and it could not be by chance that the right-wing victory against Bush).
One gets the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, someone would say, have more and more difficulty, which is not old today, to understand and therefore to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis reinforces, increases and agitates potentially inordinately.
In view of all this, to speak of a current "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda, seems frankly exaggerated.
But it is well said, keep your eyes wide open, it is not without reason.
The superglue to walk on the walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity with a super glue and, in the future, walk on walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 square centimetres, the researchers were able to hold a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers from Dayton University, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a particular structure of carbon, called carbon nano tubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that ensure the animal, a perfect adherent.
Tests performed on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it “removes easily from the wall,” says Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton’s Faculty of Engineering.
“This material could be used as a temporary adhesive,” adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on the walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but the researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since carbon nano tubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could include aerospace engineering.
So far, no superheroes.
The other research - The University of Berkeley, California, is also dedicated, in search of a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, researchers in California presented an adhesive made of hair-like microfibers, which self-cleans dust during movement on an area to ensure perfect and constant adhesion.
