Students victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The rental market for students does not have a crisis
According to the latest survey of the Sunia, the tenants union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families from origin must support," explains the head of the design office of Sunia, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the strong demand from students has distorted the market so much that a process of generalized increase has begun even for the residents.
In most cases, the rental offers also involve a series of violations: free type contracts, unregistered, no rent limit, sublettings.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of the tax, are necessary to calm the prices.
Reading in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, it goes from 650 euros minimum (zone Bande Nere), to an average value of 800 (zone Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (zone Vittoria)
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas near the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros are requested for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euro for a single) for the areas close to the other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
One can only save if one moves away in the peripheral zones: 300 euro for a bed, and 450 for a single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar zone.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a single, we spend from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for bed, it takes 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the city economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rentals are often taken by extra-community students, there is a subsequent anomaly: the rent requested from foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the cities eliminate the historic halls.
Historic movie theaters close in favor of the Multiplex.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalisation of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-halls, and the death of mono-hall consumption in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and loaded with memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of a way and so many emotions" observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, film that offers Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the juror of Cannes, and which recounted the poetry of a
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of traditional type have closed, and it is the cinemas of the main cities that have paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Roman Emilia leads with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof that confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is indeed the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but we should still guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the failed deliberation of credit in favor of traders: the state’s antecedent debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
Bologna, the first Italian city concerned about these closures, has decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote single-screen cinemas in historic centres and on the outskirts.
Among the planned regulations, there are tax measures in favor of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the limited traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and in some parking lots.
"This is an initiative that I like", observes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna putting in place other measures.
It is obvious, however, that to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that for me has always been important: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" that I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, I turn to the other side so as not to see the panels blackened by dust.
