When energy is born from the waves, now the big ones launch.
This is an outsized deposit that occupies more than 70% of the surface of the planet and now the major global energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which colossuses like Chevron have laid their eyes, and now are trying to get their hands on them.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years now, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give a great boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by sea swell operating systems.
This would be double the amount produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides..
Colossus to attack.
The first company to focus on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it looked like a real revolutionary step.
Two years from now, more and more of these companies that have always been dedicated to traditional energy are focusing on marine energy.
“Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies,” a spokesman for a company associated with the US oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and is evaluating opportunities to cooperate with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a permit deliberated by the US Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that precisely in Alaska, the U.S. continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has set up a project for new excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which travel the route of energy coming from the sea, and the amounts invested to date, although their details are not known, according to observers, a growing interest.
Tecnology to be developed.
Experts talk about a technology still in its infancy, due to the fact that marine energy does not dispel fears about the environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small, and do not seem to create any big problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a higher environmental impact.
"And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The wave thrust, which moves the sludge up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure from the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure turns a turbine which in turn feeds a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through submarine cables.
At the moment, we have four such systems in the project phase, waiting for a single federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, is already producing power for a shopping mall and parking lot using six subsea turbines from New York’s East River.
The movement of the water during the tides, rotates the blades of the turbines, creating a rotational movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Of particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Research of Electric Energy, deserves at the moment, the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable from wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it is precisely on the energy of the tides that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, with others, look towards the coasts, have invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and previews investments up to 35 million in 2009.
